post_text: Winona Area Public Schools encourages positive sportsmanship and behavior with our Facebook page. Negative and derogatory comments will be deleted.

post_text:
Are you excited for the first day of school? We are too.

Are you nervous, scared, sad, worried? Is it OK to admit that we are too?

There is so much about the upcoming year that is unknown.

But here is one thing we do know: We can get through it together.

There are going to be challenges. There is going to be uncertainty. Schoology is going to crash. The bus is going to be late. Your student will forget their mask.

But there are also going to be successes. There are going to be triumphs. There is going to be joy.

Here is what we are asking of our families this year: Share it all with us. Share your struggles. Share your joys. Share your worry. Share your happy.

Share with your teacher. Share with your principal. Share with the School Nutrition staff, your counselor, your building secretary. Share with the person who runs this Facebook account (who is also a WAPS parent, too.)

We are in this together.

Let’s have a great year.

#WinhawkProud #EveryStudent #EveryDay #Everywhere

post_text:
Today, several teachers and support staff joined members of the district leadership team for an all-day planning session for the upcoming school year. There are four groups, each taking a section of the guidance provided by the Minnesota Department of Education: Academics, Operations, Student and Family Support, and Educator Support.

We are adhering to MDH and CDC guidelines. Each group consists of less than 25 people. We have assigned entrances and exits, as well as assigned bathrooms.

We are asking lots of questions. And while we don’t have many answers, we are working toward them, and we are working toward them together.

We are not just educators. We are also parents. We are children. We are sisters and brothers. We are aunts and uncles. We are grandparents. We are grandchildren. We are your neighbors.

We want what is best for all of our students, all of our staff, and all of our community members.

We don’t know what that is just yet. But we are working on it.

#WinhawkProud #EveryStudent #EveryDay #Everywhere

post_text:
Sixteen sites. Nearly 1,000 meals a day. Hundreds and hundreds of smiling faces.

Despite facing several obstacles due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the School Nutrition staff of Winona Area Public Schools has persevered and is continuing to feed hundreds of families both in and around Winona.

The summer meal program, which was expanded this summer to deliver free student meals to 16 sites in Winona and the surrounding areas, is handing out, on average, 950 meals a day.

The sites include school sites in town as well as areas accessible to the public, including the Winona Public Library, the East Recreation Center and Sobieski Park, and living communities such as Maplewood Townhomes, Hidden Valley and the Belleview Apartments.

Deliveries are also made to rural areas, including Stockton, Rollingstone, Wilson and Ridgeway.

The meals are free to all students 18 and under, regardless of the school they attend or income level.

Read more about the summer program here: https://www.winonaschools.org/news/details/~board/district-board/post/waps-summer-meal-program-marches-on-despite-pandemic

Every summer, we ask our families to update their student's information on the parent portal. We are hoping all families will complete these updates by July 17 in order to make sure we have accurate transportation information to begin preparing bus routes.

If you have already updated your student's information, you do not need to take further action.

If you haven't updated your student's information, please check the link and follow the instructions.

If you aren't sure if you have updated your student's information, there is a way to check, and that's included in the link as well.

post_text:
This spring numerous awards were presented to the outstanding senior musicians at Winona Senior High School.

Nicole Banicki, daughter of Dawn Banicki and Jeff Banicki, received the National School Choral Award. Kaia Hamilton, daughter of Alison DeNio and Wes Hamilton, is the recipient of both the National School Orchestra Association Award and the CodaBow Award. Cade Ferstl, son of Kerri and Andrew Ferstl, received the John Philip Sousa Band Award. Katelyn Dennis, daughter of Melissa and Kevin Dennis, and Pa Cha Vang, daughter of Yang Vue and Matthew Vang, each were named recipients of the Louis Armstrong Jazz Award.

Outstanding senior band members were also recognized. They include Emily Carrie, Joella Goyette, Kole Koehler, Marissa Lindaman and Grant Wolner. Senior drum majors receiving acknowledgements are Cal Brinkman, Emily Cierzan, Caroline Dahlke, Lauren Johnson, Marissa Lindaman and Jenny Russell.

#WinhawkProud

post_text:
Distance learning didn't stop the Winona FFA Chapter from completing community service.

In this photo, Winona FFA Vice President Abigail Steinfeldt and President Bailey Harris plant the flower beds at Winona Senior High. FFA Members planted more than 200 flowers that were donated by the Winona FFA Chapter on the school grounds.

The Winona FFA was awarded a Top 10 Minnestoa FFA Chapter Community Service Award during the 2020 Online Minnesota State FFA Convention in May for donating almost 3,000 community service hours to the Winona area during the 2019-2020 FFA year.

#WinhawkProud

post_text:
Later today, the Minnesota Department of Education and Minnesota Department of Health will announce guidance for three scenarios to help us plan for the 2020-21 school year:

*Return all students to school buildings following the most current CDC and MDH guidelines.

*Return students to school buildings implementing a hybrid model of some in-person classes and some distance learning following the most current CDC and MDH guidelines.

*No students return to school buildings. Implement a distance learning model.

In late July, we expect to receive final guidance for the scenario which we will implement in the fall.

Please see the communication we sent to our families below:

https://www.winonaschools.org/parents/communications/~board/family-communications/post/what-will-school-look-like-in-the-fall-stay-tuned

As an institution in Winona for more than 150 years, we acknowledge that we are culpable in the systemic racism that has plagued our community for generations, resulting in unforgivable inequities. As Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. said in Minneapolis more than 50 years ago, “our summers of riots are caused by our winters of delay.”

We pledge to wait no more.

Please read this message from Superintendent Dr. Annette K. Freiheit to our school community.

This year, Hannah Sheridan made it into the All-State Orchestra cello section for a second year in a row. String bass player Grant Hamsund also made it into the All-State Orchestra. Daniel Florness was accepted into the All-State Band on tuba.
